- Occurs in 1 rows (26): ["Here is the step-by-step legal analysis of the situation under Swiss Law.\n\n**Clarify the facts**\nX is the original owner of a car. In April 2016, the car was stolen by V. In June 2016, V sold the car to B. X now seeks to recover the car from B, who currently possesses it.\n\n**Issue Identification**\nThe legal issue is determining the specific causes of action available to an owner (X) to recover a stolen chattel from a third-party purchaser (B) under the Swiss Civil Code (CC). Specifically, whether X can rely on remedies based on possession, ownership, contract, or general principles of law.\n\n**Rule Explanation**\nUnder Swiss Law, two primary avenues exist for the recovery of an object in this context:\n1.  **Action based on Property (Vindication):** According to **Art. 641 para. 2 CC**, the owner of an object can claim it back from anyone who withholds it without a valid legal ground (*rei vindicatio*).\n2.  **Action based on the Right to Possession:** According to **Art. 934 para. 1 CC**, a person from whom a chattel has been stolen (or otherwise lost against their will) may reclaim it from any current possessor within five years. This is a specific action derived from possession law (*Fahrnisklage*).\n\n**Application and Reasoning**\n*   **Regarding (i) Action for restitution based on right to possession:** Since the car was stolen from X, it is considered a chattel lost against the owner's will. Under Art. 934 CC, X has the specific statutory right to reclaim the car from B (even if B acted in good faith) for a period of five years. This constitutes an action based on the right to possession.\n*   **Regarding (ii) Action for restitution based on property:** As the car was stolen, V could not transfer valid title to B (a thief cannot transfer ownership). Therefore, X remains the legal owner of the car. As the owner, X is entitled to file a vindication action (Art. 641 CC) to demand the return of the property.\n*   **Regarding (iii) Contract law:** There is no contractual relationship between X and B. The contract of sale was between V and B. Therefore, X cannot base a claim on contract law.\n*   **Regarding (iv) Abuse of rights:** The principle of abuse of rights (Art. 2 CC) is a corrective mechanism for the misuse of legal rights. It is not a primary cause of action for the recovery of property and does not apply to the facts at hand.\n\n**Eliminate Incorrect Answers**\n*   **A (i only):** Incorrect because it ignores the property-based claim (vindication), which is also valid.\n*   **B (i, iii, and iv):** Incorrect because contract law and abuse of rights are not applicable grounds for recovery here.\n*   **C (iii and iv):** Incorrect for the reasons stated above; neither contract nor abuse of rights applies.\n*   **D (i and ii):** Correct. Swiss law allows for a concurrence of actions. X can sue based on their status as the dispossessed former possessor (Art. 934 CC) and as the current legal owner (Art. 641 CC).\n\n**Conclusion**\nX can regain possession through an action based on the right to possession (Art. 934 CC) and an action based on property ownership (Art. 641 CC). Therefore, both i and ii are correct means.\n\nFinal Answer: ###D###"]
