\n\n**Statement iii: The testator may attach burdens or conditions to the disposition in his/her last will, the fulfilment of which may be requested by any interested party once the disposition becomes effective.**\n*   **Rule:** **Art. 482 para. 1 of the Swiss Civil Code (CC)** states that a testator may attach burdens (*Auflagen*) or conditions (*Bedingungen*) to a disposition. It explicitly grants any interested person the right to request the fulfillment of a burden once the disposition has taken effect.\n*   **Application:** The statement accurately reflects the statutory provision regarding the enforcement of burdens attached to testamentary dispositions.\n*   **Result:** Statement iii is **correct**.\n\n**Statement iv: A contract suffering from a fundamental error is voidable by the party that was acting under error.**\n*   **Rule:** **Art. 23 of the Swiss Code of Obligations (CO)** states that a contract is not binding on the party that was acting under a fundamental error (*wesentlicher Irrtum*). Under Swiss law (specifically Art. 31 CO), the contract is treated as valid until the party in error declares to the other party that they do not intend to be bound (within one year). This mechanism is legally characterized as \"voidability\" (or *Anfechtbarkeit* / *Ungültigkeitstheorie*).\n*   **Application:** The statement correctly describes the legal consequence of a fundamental error: the erroneous party has the power to invalidate (void) the contract.\n*   **Result:** Statement iv is **correct**.\n\n### Eliminate Incorrect Answers\nThe question asks for the statement(s) that is/are **incorrect**. Based on the analysis above, only statement **i** is incorrect.\n\n*   **A) i and iv:** Incorrect choice. While i is incorrect, iv is correct.\n*   **B) iv:** Incorrect choice. Statement iv is correct.\n*   **D) ii, iii, and iv:** Incorrect choice. These statements are all correct.\n\n### Conclusion\nStatement **i** is the only incorrect statement because it misidentifies the content and structure of the Digest (which contains jurist writings in 50 books) with the Codex (which contains Imperial decisions in 12 books). Therefore, choice C is the correct answer.\n\nFinal Answer: ###C###"]
