 statement claims a person lacks capacity if they are \"below a certain age.\" This implies a fixed age threshold. Swiss law uses the term \"young age\" (*Kindesalter*) and applies a relative standard based on the complexity of the act, not a specific numerical age limit.\n    -   **Formal Errors:** The statement contains a syntax error (\"According to the of the Swiss Civil Code\") and repeats the final sentence (\"Capacity of judgment is a key concept...\"). These errors, combined with the imprecise legal definition, make the statement incorrect.\n-   **Analysis of Statement ii:**\n    -   Alexandra is tax-resident in Zug. Under the residence principle, she is taxed in Zug on her worldwide income, including the US dividends.\n    -   Working in Zurich does not shift the taxation of investment income (movable assets) to Zurich; it remains at the place of residence.\n    -   The principle of totality of income correctly explains why the dividends are included in the taxable base.\n    -   Therefore, Statement ii is legally correct.\n\n**Eliminate Incorrect Answers**\n-   **A) ii:** Incorrect choice because statement ii is legally correct.\n-   **B) none of the statements:** Incorrect because statement i is incorrect.\n-   **D) i and ii:** Incorrect because statement ii is correct.\n-   **C) i:** Correct choice. Statement i is the only incorrect statement due to the legal inaccuracy regarding age limits and drafting errors.\n\n**Conclusion**\nStatement i is incorrect because it mischaracterizes the condition of \"young age\" as being \"below a certain age\" (implying a fixed limit contrary to the relative nature of capacity in Swiss law) and contains grammatical flaws. Statement ii is correct. Therefore, only statement i is incorrect.\n\nFinal Answer: ###C###"]
