he owner of the land/chattel, while the finder is only entitled to a statutory reward.\n*Reasoning:* Swiss law explicitly rejected the Roman solution of co-ownership (which can be impractical) in favor of assigning full ownership to the landowner. In Swiss legal theory, this is frequently cited as a classic example of where the modern legislator (Eugen Huber) chose to depart from Roman legal tradition.\n*Conclusion:* This statement is **correct**.\n\n**5. Analyze Statement iv**\n*Statement:* \"A measure can still be imposed on an offender who lacks criminal capacity.\"\n*Rule:* Under the Swiss Criminal Code (SCC), an offender who lacks criminal capacity (*Schuldunfähigkeit*) at the time of the act cannot be punished (i.e., no prison sentence or fine, per Art. 19 para. 1 SCC). However, Art. 19 para. 3 and Art. 59 et seq. SCC explicitly allow the court to impose therapeutic **measures** (*Massnahmen*), such as institutional treatment, if necessary for public safety or the offender's health.\n*Conclusion:* This statement is **correct**.\n\n**6. Eliminate Incorrect Answers**\nThe question asks for the **incorrect** statement(s).\n*   **Statement i** is incorrect.\n*   **Statements ii, iii, and iv** are correct.\n\n*   **A) iii and iv:** Incorrect choice because both iii and iv are correct statements.\n*   **B) i, ii, and iii:** Incorrect choice because ii and iii are correct statements.\n*   **C) i, ii, and iv:** Incorrect choice because ii and iv are correct statements.\n*   **D) i:** This choice correctly identifies statement i as the only incorrect statement.\n\n**Conclusion**\nStatement i is the only incorrect statement because a limited partnership must have at least one partner with unlimited liability.\n\nFinal Answer: ###D###"]
