e to the principle of freedom of contract, \"innominate contracts\" exist which mix elements of different contracts or are entirely unique. Not every contract fits into the named types in the CO.\n*   **Statement ii:** False. An estimation of value is an expert opinion. While the delivery of the report is a result, the content (the value) is subjective to the expert's assessment and market fluctuations. It is not a \"measurable result that can be guaranteed\" in the strict legal sense of a contract for work. Thus, it is treated as a mandate.\n*   **Statement iii:** False. According to Art. 394 para. 3 CO, a mandate does not require remuneration to be valid; it can be performed for free.\n*   **Statement iv:** True. Since the contract is classified as a mandate (involving a service of expertise/trust), Katrina has the mandatory right to revoke it at any time under Art. 404 para. 1 CO.\n*   **Statement v:** True. While Katrina has the right to revoke at any time, Art. 404 para. 2 CO stipulates that if she does so at an \"inopportune juncture\" (e.g., after Dr. Genius has declined other work to focus on this, but before he has finished), she is liable for the damages caused by the timing of the revocation.\n\n**Eliminate Incorrect Answers**\n*   **A) i, ii, and v:** Incorrect because i and ii are false.\n*   **B) i, iii, and iv:** Incorrect because i and iii are false.\n*   **D) iii and iv:** Incorrect because iii is false.\n\n**Conclusion**\nStatements iv and v are the only correct statements based on Swiss contract law regarding mandates. Therefore, choice C is the correct answer.\n\nFinal Answer: ###C###"]
