ho live in a legally and factually unseparated marriage are subject to **mandatory joint taxation** (*Faktorenaddition*). Their income and wealth are added together to determine the applicable tax rate.\n    *   **No Choice:** Unlike in some other jurisdictions, Swiss law does not offer an option to choose between \"married filing jointly\" or \"married filing separately.\" Separate taxation is only applied if the spouses live separately or are divorced.\n\n### Application and Reasoning\n*   **Analyzing Statement (i):** \"Since Eric works in the canton of Zürich but lives in the canton of Aargau, his income from employment may be taxed by the canton of Zürich.\"\n    *   Eric's tax residence is Aargau. Under the prohibition of inter-cantonal double taxation, the canton of work (Zürich) has no right to tax the employment income of a resident of another canton (Aargau). The tax sovereignty belongs to Aargau. Even if tax at source is physically deducted in Zürich, it is levied *for* Aargau. Therefore, the statement that Zürich taxes the income is legally **incorrect** in the context of tax jurisdiction.\n\n*   **Analyzing Statement (ii):** \"Eric and Clara can choose whether they want to be taxed together or separately.\"\n    *   Eric and Clara are married and live together in the same house. Under Swiss law, they must be taxed jointly. They do not have a choice. Therefore, this statement is **incorrect**.\n\n### Eliminate Incorrect Answers\n*   **A) ii:** Incorrect, because statement ii is false (joint taxation is mandatory).\n*   **B) i:** Incorrect, because statement i is false (taxation is at residence, not work).\n*   **C) i and ii:** Incorrect, because both statements are false.\n*   **D) none of the statements:** Correct, as both statements i and ii are false based on Swiss tax law principles.\n\n### Conclusion\nStatement (i) is false because employment income is taxed at the place of residence (Aargau), not the place of work (Zürich). Statement (ii) is false because married couples living together cannot choose their filing status; joint taxation is mandatory. Therefore, none of the statements are applicable.\n\nFinal Answer: ###D###"]
