t is possible for parties in Switzerland to litigate in person (i.e. without being represented by a lawyer) before all civil courts including the Federal Court.\"*\n    *   **Legal Issue:** Legal representation in civil proceedings (Monopoly of lawyers vs. Self-representation).\n    *   **Rule:** In Swiss civil procedure, parties generally have the right to represent themselves (*pro se*). While Art. 40 of the Federal Supreme Court Act (BGG) stipulates that *professional* representation is restricted to authorized lawyers, it does not impose a mandatory requirement for parties to be represented by a lawyer (*Anwaltszwang*) in civil matters. Parties capable of acting may conduct their own appeals, although it is practically difficult.\n    *   **Conclusion:** This statement is **Correct**.\n\n*   **Statement iv:** *\"Intention is defined in the specific part of the Criminal Code.\"*\n    *   **Legal Issue:** Structure of the Swiss Criminal Code (StGB).\n    *   **Rule:** The Swiss Criminal Code is divided into a General Part (Book 1, Art. 1–110) and a Specific/Special Part (Book 2, Art. 111 onwards). The definitions of fundamental concepts like intention (*Vorsatz*) and negligence (*Fahrlässigkeit*) are found in Art. 12 StGB, which is located in the **General Part**.\n    *   **Conclusion:** This statement is **Incorrect**.\n\n**3. Evaluation of Choices**\nBased on the analysis:\n*   Statement i is **Incorrect**.\n*   Statement ii is **Correct**.\n*   Statement iii is **Correct**.\n*   Statement iv is **Incorrect**.\n\nThe question asks: *\"Which of the following statements is/are incorrect?\"*\nThe incorrect statements are **i and iv**.\nHowever, looking at the provided choices:\nA) i and ii\nB) i and iii\nC) iv\nD) ii and iii\n\nNone of the choices correspond to \"i and iv\".\n*   Choice D corresponds exactly to the set of **Correct** statements (ii and iii).\n*   In multiple-choice questions of this type, it is highly probable that the prompt contains a typo and intended to ask \"Which of the following statements is/are **correct**?\", or the options provided are meant to identify the valid legal propositions. Given that statements i and iv are factually and fundamentally wrong in Swiss Law, and statements ii and iii are accurate, Choice D is the only logical answer derived from a correct legal analysis of the statements.\n\nIf we were forced to answer \"incorrect\", no option fits. Assuming the standard format of such legal exams where D combines the two valid statements:\n\n**Conclusion:** Statements ii and iii are correct. Choice D represents these statements.\n\nFinal Answer: ###D###"]
