as concluded, performance is objectively impossible for anyone. Under Art. 20 CO, a contract with impossible content is null and void.\n-   **Statement iii:** Correct. Art. 216 para. 1 CO explicitly states that a contract for the sale of immovable property is valid only if done as a public deed.\n-   **Statement iv:** Correct. Mistaking a forgery for a genuine Picasso is a classic example of an error in necessary qualities (substantive error) under Art. 24 para. 1 no. 4 CO. This is a fundamental error. The party can avoid the contract within one year of discovering the error (Art. 31 CO).\n\n**Eliminate Incorrect Answers:**\n-   **Statement i** is false because of the one-year deadline. Therefore, any choice including (i) is incorrect. This eliminates B and C.\n-   **Statements ii, iii, and iv** are all legally correct.\n-   Choice A includes ii, iii, and iv.\n\n**Conclusion:**\nStatements ii, iii, and iv are correct. Statement i is incorrect due to the time limit constraint. Therefore, Choice A is the correct answer.\n\nFinal Answer: ###A###"]
