e federal system and do not violate the principle of equality (Art. 8 BV).\n3.  **Place of Taxation (Employment):** For dependent employment, the right to tax lies with the canton of the taxpayer's main tax domicile (residence), defined by the center of vital interests (Art. 127 para. 3 BV; Inter-cantonal double taxation case law). The place of work generally does not acquire tax sovereignty for dependent employment income unless a specific secondary tax domicile (e.g., weekly residence with specific conditions) is established. A 3-month temporary assignment typically does not shift the center of vital interests or create a secondary tax domicile.\n4.  **Education Deductions:** Under Art. 33 para. 1 lit. j DBG, costs for further education (Weiterbildung) and retraining are deductible if they are related to the taxpayer's profession. Since 2016, the distinction between initial and further education has been relaxed, focusing on the professional orientation of the course.\n\n**Application and Reasoning**\n- **Statement i:** Marcus and Susanne are both earners (teacher and analyst). Aggregating their incomes for federal tax purposes likely pushes them into a higher progression bracket than if they were taxed individually. While specific deductions exist, the \"marriage penalty\" is a factual reality for many dual-income couples at the federal level. Thus, their belief is well-founded and the statement is correct.\n- **Statement ii:** The couple believes differing rates infringe the Constitution. Legally, tax competition is constitutional. Therefore, the legal opinion expressed in the statement is incorrect. In the context of such questions, a statement asserting a false legal conclusion is treated as incorrect.\n- **Statement iii:** Susanne lives in Zurich. Her work in Geneva was temporary (3 months) and she is an employee. The right to tax this income remains exclusively with her canton of residence, Zurich. Geneva does not have the right to tax this income. Thus, the statement that the income is taxable in Zurich is correct.\n- **Statement iv:** Marcus takes the course to enable a professional exchange. This establishes a direct professional link (beruflicher Zusammenhang). Consequently, the costs constitute deductible professional education expenses. The statement is correct.\n\n**Eliminate Incorrect Answers**\n- **Statement i** is correct (included in all options).\n- **Statement ii** is incorrect (opinion is legally wrong).\n- **Statement iii** is correct (taxation at residence).\n- **Statement iv** is correct (deductible education costs).\n\n- **Choice B (i)** is incorrect because it omits iii and iv.\n- **Choice C (i and iv)** is incorrect because it omits iii.\n- **Choice D (i and iii)** is incorrect because it omits iv.\n- **Choice A (i, iii, and iv)** includes all the correct statements.\n\n**Conclusion**\nStatements i, iii, and iv are legally correct. Statement ii is incorrect because differing cantonal tax rates are constitutional.\n\nFinal Answer: ###A###"]
