n**Statement ii: Dividends from a French company.**\n*   **Rule:** Residents of Switzerland are taxed on their worldwide income. Dividends from shares represent income from movable capital (Art. 20 DBG).\n*   **Application:** There is no general exemption for foreign dividends in Swiss tax law. While a Double Taxation Treaty might regulate withholding taxes, the income itself remains taxable in the state of residence (Switzerland).\n*   **Conclusion:** The statement that they are exempted is **Incorrect**.\n\n**Statement iii: Inheritance.**\n*   **Rule:** Under Art. 24 lit. a DBG, inheritance and gifts are explicitly exempt from federal *income* tax. Switzerland does not levy a federal inheritance tax. Inheritance taxes are levied at the cantonal level.\n*   **Application:** While Anne may have to pay cantonal inheritance tax, she does *not* have to pay federal income tax on the inheritance.\n*   **Conclusion:** The statement is **Incorrect**.\n\n**Statement iv: Employment income.**\n*   **Rule:** For dependent employment, the right to tax income lies with the canton of residence (tax domicile). The canton of work (Bern) does not have the right to tax the income of a resident of another canton (Zurich), provided the person returns home daily (daily commuter).\n*   **Application:** Anne lives in Zurich and commutes daily. Therefore, Zurich has the exclusive right to tax her employment income. Bern cannot tax it.\n*   **Conclusion:** The statement that it is subject to the income tax of the Canton of Bern is **Incorrect**.\n\n### Eliminate Incorrect Answers\n*   **A) i, iii, and iv:** Incorrect because iii (federal tax on inheritance) and iv (Bern tax on employment) are false.\n*   **B) ii and iv:** Incorrect because ii (dividend exemption) and iv are false.\n*   **C) ii:** Incorrect because dividends are taxable.\n*   **D) i:** This matches our analysis. Only statement i is legally correct.\n\n### Conclusion\nStatement i correctly identifies the tax liability for real estate located in another canton (taxable at federal level and situs canton). All other statements contain legal errors regarding tax sovereignty or the definition of taxable income.\n\nFinal Answer: ###D###"]
