rate taxation.\n\n**Application and Reasoning**\n*   **Statement i (True):** Although the income from the Amsterdam apartment is not taxed directly, Eric must declare it. Swiss tax authorities need this information to calculate the correct tax rate applied to his Swiss income (exemption with progression).\n*   **Statement ii (False):** Switzerland applies the principle of family taxation. Married couples living together are legally required to file jointly; they cannot choose separate taxation.\n*   **Statement iii (False):** Eric is a daily commuter living in Aargau. Under the inter-cantonal rules preventing double taxation, the right to tax employment income lies exclusively with the canton of residence (Aargau). The canton of work (Zürich) does not have the right to tax this income.\n*   **Statement iv (False):** The prohibition of double taxation (Art. 127 para. 3 BV) prevents two cantons from taxing the same object (horizontal conflict). It does not prohibit the standard vertical system where the Confederation, Canton, and Commune all levy taxes on income.\n*   **Statement v (True):** Income from foreign real estate is allocated to the state where the property is located (Netherlands). Therefore, it is exempt from Swiss income tax (it is \"not taxable\" in terms of payment, though relevant for the rate).\n\n**Eliminate Incorrect Answers**\n*   **A) iv and v:** Incorrect because statement iv is false (the three-tier system is constitutional).\n*   **B) iii, iv, and v:** Incorrect because iii (workplace taxation) and iv (unconstitutional triple taxation) are false.\n*   **C) iii:** Incorrect because the canton of work (Zürich) cannot tax the income of a resident of Aargau.\n*   **D) i and v:** Correct. Both statements accurately reflect the treatment of foreign real estate: it must be declared (i) but is not itself subject to tax payment (v).\n\n**Conclusion**\nStatements i and v are the only legally correct statements. Eric must declare the foreign income for ra