 on the maximum amount deductible (e.g., the federal cap of CHF 3,000 introduced via the FABI vote), the right to claim the deduction for the expense remains.*\n\n### Application and Reasoning\n*   **Analyzing Statement (i):** \"In Switzerland, regardless of the canton, Eric will be subject to a cantonal net wealth tax. On the federal level, however, no net wealth tax is levied.\"\n    *   As Eric will be a tax resident, he is subject to unlimited tax liability.\n    *   Since every canton levies a wealth tax and the federal government does not, this statement is legally accurate in its entirety.\n\n*   **Analyzing Statement (ii):** \"If Eric decides to live in Wollerau (canton of Schwyz) and not in the city of Zürich, he will be allowed to deduct the travel expenses (daily travel by train from Wollerau to Zürich) from his income from employment.\"\n    *   Living in Wollerau and working in Zürich necessitates a commute.\n    *   Under Swiss tax law, the cost of public transport for commuting is a recognized professional deduction.\n    *   Therefore, Eric is allowed to deduct these expenses (subject to statutory caps on the *amount*, but the statement only asserts he is allowed to deduct the expenses, which is true).\n\n### Eliminate Incorrect Answers\n*   **A) ii:** This implies statement (i) is incorrect. Since statement (i) is correct regarding the structure of wealth tax, this choice is wrong.\n*   **B) i:** This implies statement (ii) is incorrect. Since commuting costs are deductible professional expenses, statement (ii) is correct, making this choice wrong.\n*   **C) none of the statements:** Since both statements are correct, this is wrong.\n*   **D) i and ii:** Both statements accurately reflect Swiss tax law. Statement (i) correctly identifies the levels at which wealth tax is levied, and statement (ii) correctly identifies the deductibility of commuting costs.\n\n### Conclusion\nBoth statements provided in the context are correct based on Swiss tax law. 