- Occurs in 1 rows (335): ["Here is the step-by-step reasoning for the question:\n\n**Clarify the facts**\nDr. Genius has entered into an agreement with Katrina to estimate the value of a real estate property in the canton of Lucerne. The core of the transaction is the provision of a professional valuation or expert opinion regarding the property's worth.\n\n**Issue Identification**\nThe central legal issues are:\n1.  **Contract Classification:** Does this agreement constitute a simple mandate (*Auftrag*) or a contract for work and services (*Werkvertrag*)?\n2.  **Termination Rights:** Under what conditions can Katrina terminate the contract?\n3.  **Contract Typology:** Are all contracts under Swiss law limited to the specific types listed in the Code of Obligations?\n\n**Rule Explanation**\n1.  **Freedom of Contract (Art. 19 CO):** Swiss law recognizes the principle of freedom of contract. Parties can create \"innominate contracts\" (*Innominatkontrakte*) that do not fit strictly into the statutory types defined in the Second Division of the Swiss Code of Obligations (CO), or mix elements of them.\n2.  **Mandate vs. Contract for Work:**\n    *   **Mandate (*Auftrag*, Art. 394 et seq. CO):** The agent undertakes to conduct the business or perform the services with due care. Crucially, the agent does not guarantee a specific successful result, only diligent conduct. A key feature of the mandate is the mandatory right of either party to revoke the contract at any time (Art. 404 CO).\n    *   **Contract for Work (*Werkvertrag*, Art. 363 et seq. CO):** The contractor undertakes to produce a specific \"work\" (a measurable, objective result) in exchange for payment. The contractor guarantees the successful production of this result.\n3.  **Nature of Valuations:** In Swiss legal doctrine and case law, an expert opinion (*Gutachten*) regarding value is often classified as a mandate. This is because a valuation is an estimate based on professional judgment and market factors; it is not an objectively measurable result that can be \"guaranteed\" in the same way a physical construction can be. The expert owes a duty of care (diligence), not a duty of result (*Erfolg*).\n\n**Application and Reasoning**\n*   **Statement i:** \"Every contract falls under one of the types in the second division of the Swiss Code of Obligations.\"\n    *   This is **incorrect**. Due to the freedom of contract (Art. 19 CO), parties can conclude innominate contracts or mixed contracts that are not explicitly listed in the Second Division.\n*   **Statement iii:** \"Estimating the value of a real estate is an agreement on a measurable result that can be guaranteed.\"\n    *   This is **incorrect**. A property valuation is an opinion or estimate. While the delivery of a report is a physical act, the core service is the intellectual assessment. One cannot objectively \"guarantee\" a market value as a successful result; one can only guarantee that the proper methods were used diligently. Therefore, this falls under the rules of a Mandate, not a Contract for Work.\n*   **Statement ii:** \"Katrina can revoke the contract with Dr. Genius at any time.\"\n    *   Since the contract is classified as a Mandate (due to the lack of a guaranteed objective result), Art. 404 CO applies. Art. 404(1) CO states that a mandate may be revoked or terminated by either party at any time. Even if it were a Contract for Work, Art. 377 CO allows the customer to withdraw before completion, but Art. 404 is the specific \"at any time\" right associated with the nature of this service. Thus, this statement is **correct**.\n\n**Eliminate Incorrect Answers**\n*   **A) i, ii, and iii:** Incorrect because i and iii are false.\n*   **C) iii:** Incorrect because iii is false (valuation is not a guaranteed result).\n*   **D) ii and iii:** Incorrect because iii is false.\n*   **E) I don't know:** Incorrect.\n\n**Conclusion**\nStatement i is false (innominate contracts exist). Statement iii is false (valuation is a mandate/service of diligence, not a guaranteed result). Statement ii is true (mandates can be revoked at any time under Art. 404 CO). Therefore, only statement ii is applicable.\n\nFinal Answer: ###B###"]
