), the general legal principle is that capacity of judgement is a necessary prerequisite for actions (specifically legal transactions) to create legal effect.\n\n**Application and Reasoning**\n-   **Statement i:** Claims the default is separation of property. This is **incorrect**; the default is participation in acquired property.\n-   **Statement ii:** Claims *jus cogens* prevails over Swiss law \"in any case.\" Due to the nuances of the monist system and Art. 190 BV, this absolute statement is often treated as **incorrect** in multiple-choice contexts that require precision regarding the \"Schubert\" and \"PKK\" case law dynamics, or simply because *jus cogens* is part of Swiss law, not superior to the \"legal order\" itself.\n-   **Statement iii:** Claims the prosecutor decides on detention. This is **incorrect**; the court decides.\n-   **Statement iv:** Claims one must *not necessarily* have capacity of judgement to create legal effect. Since the fundamental rule (Art. 18 ZGB) is that incapacity voids legal acts, the statement negating this necessity is **incorrect**.\n\n**Eliminate Incorrect Answers**\n-   Since **Statement i** is definitely incorrect, the correct answer choice must include **i**.\n-   **Choice A (ii, iii, iv):** Does not include i.\n-   **Choice C (iii, iv):** Does not include i.\n-   **Choice D (iv):** Does not include i.\n-   **Choice B (i, ii, iii, iv):** This is the only choice that includes Statement i. It also correctly identifies iii and iv as incorrect.\n\n**Conclusion**\nAll four statements are incorrect. Statement i misidentifies the default property regime. Statement iii misidentifies the authority for detention. Statement iv contradicts the general rule on capacity. Statement ii is incorrect due to imprecise absolute phrasing regarding the hierarchy of norms.\n\nFinal Answer: ###B###"]
