 upon the death of a spouse or the implementation of a different regime. Divorce is a statutory ground for dissolution (retroactive to the date the divorce petition was filed).\n    *   *Application:* The statement accurately reflects the legal consequence of divorce on the property regime.\n    *   *Conclusion:* Statement iii is **correct**.\n\n5.  **Analyze Statement iv:**\n    *   *Statement:* \"When diverging interpretations of a contract of both parties are equally admissible, there is no consent but rather dissent and therefore no contract has ever come to legal existence. Swiss contract law is governed by different principles.\"\n    *   *Rule:* Swiss contract law relies on the **principle of trust** (*Vertrauensprinzip*) to establish a contract (normative consensus) when actual intent differs. However, if interpretations are \"equally admissible\" (ambiguous) and the principle of trust cannot establish a single meaning, there is no consensus (dissent), and thus no contract.\n    *   *Application:* The first sentence describes the result of unresolvable ambiguity (no contract). The second sentence (\"Swiss contract law is governed by different principles\") likely refers to the theoretical distinction that Swiss law uses the *objective/normative* approach (trust principle) rather than the purely *subjective* will theory described in the first part, even if the outcome (no contract) is the same in this specific edge case of equal admissibility. In the context of exam questions, this highlights the specific methodology of Swiss law.\n    *   *Conclusion:* Statement iv is considered **correct** in this context (or at least, iii is definitely correct and i/ii are definitely incorrect, forcing this selection).\n\n6.  **Eliminate Incorrect Answers:**\n    *   **A (ii, iii, and iv):** Incorrect because ii is false.\n    *   **B (ii):** Incorrect because ii is false.\n    *   **C (i, ii, and iii):** Incorrect because i and ii are false.\n    *   **D (iii and iv):** T