Art. 148 para. 2) and that federal acts require the consent of both chambers (Art. 156 para. 2).\n*   **Verdict:** This statement is **correct**.\n\n**Analysis of Statement iii:**\n\"Swiss commercial law requires a commercial partnership to act in its own name in legal proceedings.\"\n*   **Legal Source:** Swiss Code of Obligations (CO), specifically regarding General Partnerships (Kollektivgesellschaft) and Limited Partnerships (Kommanditgesellschaft).\n*   **Reasoning:**\n    1.  **Legal Personality:** Commercial partnerships in Switzerland (General and Limited Partnerships) are **not** legal entities (juridical persons). They do not have their \"own name\" in the strict legal sense that a corporation (AG/SA) does. Instead, they have a **firm name** (Firma).\n    2.  **Procedural Capacity:** While they are not legal entities, Article 562 of the CO grants them the capacity to sue and be sued. However, the statute specifies that the partnership may sue and be sued \"under its firm name\" (unter ihrer Firma), not \"in its own name\". This distinction emphasizes the lack of full legal personality.\n    3.  **Requirement:** The statement says the law \"requires\" it to act in its own name. Since it technically acts under its firm name (as a procedural privilege for the group of partners), the phrasing \"act in its own name\" is technically incorrect in the context of Swiss commercial law distinctions. Furthermore, if \"commercial partnership\" were interpreted to include Simple Partnerships used in commerce, the statement would be false because Simple Partnerships cannot sue or be sued as an entity at all.\n*   **Verdict:** This statement is **incorrect**.\n\n**Conclusion:**\nStatement i is incorrect due to the implication of a fixed age for capacity of judgement. Statement iii is incorrect due to the distinction between acting \"in its own name\" (legal entity) and \"under its firm name\" (partnership), and the lack of legal personality. Statement ii is correct.\n\nTherefore, statements i and iii are incorrect.\n\nFinal Answer: ###B###"]
