ability until the child reaches majority, unless specific circumstances apply (which are not indicated here). However, looking closely at the text of statement (ii), it says \"When Alexandra was born...\". It does not explicitly state her current age. If she is an adult, the statement is correct. If she is a minor, the income is taxed, but usually attributed to the parents.\n   \n   *Re-evaluating Statement (ii) based on standard exam logic:*\n   The statement says \"Alexandra lives... works... commutes.\" This implies she is an adult or at least old enough to work and commute independently. If she works, she has earned income. The statement says she received shares *when she was born*. It does not say she is currently a child. It implies she is currently a working taxpayer.\n   Therefore, as a tax resident of Zug, she is subject to unlimited tax liability. The principle of totality of income means her worldwide income (including US dividends) is subject to income tax at all three levels (Federal, Cantonal, Communal).\n\n   *Let's look for a trick.*\n   Is there a Double Taxation Treaty issue? Generally, dividends are taxable in the residence state, though the source state may withhold tax (creditable). The statement says it is \"subject to income tax,\" which is true.\n   Is there an issue with the \"principle of totality\"? Yes, that is the correct term.\n   \n   *Let's re-read Statement (i) very carefully.*\n   \"The Federal Assembly (Parliament) consists of two chambers, the National Council and the Council of States. The two chambers are equal and have similar powers. In particular, both chambers must agree on the enactment of federal acts. The two chambers are equal and have similar powers. In particular, both chambers must agree on the enactment of federal acts.\"\n   The text repeats itself. While stylistically poor, the legal content is factually *correct*. The chambers are equal, and they must agree.\n\n   *Let's re-read Statement (ii) for potential \"inco