\n    This statement is **false**. Due to the principle of freedom of contract (Art. 19 CO), parties can conclude innominate contracts (e.g., license agreements, leasing) that do not fit strictly into the nominate types listed in the Second Division of the CO. Therefore, the list in the CO is not exhaustive.\n\n*   **Statement ii:** \"Katrina can revoke the contract with Dr. Genius at any time.\"\n    To evaluate this, we must classify the contract. A real estate valuation involves professional expertise, discretion, and estimation. While it results in a report, the core of the obligation is the diligent application of expert knowledge rather than the production of a guaranteed physical \"success\" or objective result (which would characterize a Contract for Work). Consequently, Swiss legal doctrine and case law typically classify expert valuations (Schätzungen) as **Mandates (Auftrag)**.\n    Since the contract is a mandate, **Art. 404 para. 1 CO** applies, which grants either party the mandatory right to terminate the contract **at any time**. Therefore, this statement is **true**.\n\n**Eliminate Incorrect Answers**\n*   **A) i and ii:** Incorrect because statement i is false.\n*   **B) i:** Incorrect because statement i is false.\n*   **D) none of the statements:** Incorrect because statement ii is true.\n\n**Conclusion**\nStatement i is incorrect because innominate contracts exist. Statement ii is correct because a real estate valuation is treated as a mandate, which is subject to the mandatory termination right of Art. 404 CO.\n\nFinal Answer: ###C###"]
