on and the Federal Law on the Harmonization of Direct Taxes, individuals are taxed at their place of main tax domicile (residence). The canton where the work is performed (Zürich) generally has no right to tax the employment income of a resident of another canton (Aargau), barring specific exceptions not present here (e.g., weekly residents).\n4.  **Swiss Tax System Structure:** The Swiss tax system is federalist, comprising three levels: Federal, Cantonal, and Communal. This vertical plurality is constitutionally mandated and does not constitute prohibited \"double taxation.\" The constitutional prohibition of inter-cantonal double taxation (Art. 127 para. 3 BV) prevents two *cantons* from taxing the same object for the same period (horizontal conflict), not the levying of taxes by different levels of government.\n\n### Application and Reasoning\n-   **Statement i:** Eric and Clara are married and live together. Swiss law mandates joint taxation. They cannot choose to be taxed separately. -> **False.**\n-   **Statement ii:** While Switzerland likely does not tax the Amsterdam rental income directly (due to the allocation of taxing rights to the Netherlands), Eric and Clara must declare this income in their Swiss tax return. The Swiss authorities need this information to calculate the correct tax rate applied to their Swiss income (progression proviso). -> **True.**\n-   **Statement iii:** Eric is a commuter. He lives in Aargau and works in Zürich. The right to tax employment income lies exclusively with the canton of residence (Aargau). Zürich cannot tax this income. (Even if Eric is subject to source tax as a foreign national, the tax is levied according to the tariffs of the residence canton, and the revenue belongs to the residence canton). -> **False.**\n-   **Statement iv:** The existence of federal, cantonal, and communal taxes is the standard legal structure in Switzerland. It does not violate the prohibition of inter-cantonal double taxation, which applies to conflicts between cantons, not vertical accumulation. -> **False.**\n\n### Eliminate Incorrect Answers\n-   **A) i:** Incorrect because statement i is false (joint taxation is mandatory).\n-   **B) i and ii:** Incorrect because statement i is false.\n-   **C) i, ii, iii, and iv:** Incorrect because statements i, iii, and iv are false.\n-   **E) I don't know:** Incorrect.\n\n### Conclusion\nOnly statement ii is legally correct. Eric and Clara must declare their foreign income for the purpose of determining the tax rate, even if that specific income is not taxed in Switzerland.\n\nFinal Answer: ###D###"]
