ect?\"\nCandidates: ii and iv.\nChoice C (iv) contains \"Always\".\nChoice B (ii) contains \"Generally\".\n\"Always\" statements that are false are logically stronger candidates for \"The Incorrect Statement\" than \"Generally\" statements that are false (which might be argued as 'imprecise').\nTherefore, C is the best guess.\n\n**Conclusion:**\nStatement i is Correct (Abstract = annulment, Concrete = repeal decision).\nStatement ii is Incorrect (Civil proceedings = Adversarial maxim generally).\nStatement iii is Correct (Reciprocity not required).\nStatement iv is Incorrect (Cantonal Admin Court -> Federal Supreme Court).\n\nSince I must choose between B (ii) and C (iv), and iv is structurally and absolutely wrong (\"always\"), while ii is wrong regarding the general principle but has significant exceptions in practice, C is the most robust choice for the \"incorrect\" statement.\n\nFinal check:\nCould \"iv\" be correct? No.\nCould \"ii\" be correct? Only if \"generally\" is interpreted loosely to mean \"in many common types of cases\".\nCould \"i\" be incorrect? No.\nCould \"iii\" be incorrect? Only if pre-2019 law applies. (If so, A would be \"Correct and Incorrect\").\n\nTherefore, C is the logical choice for the incorrect statement.\n\nFinal Answer: ###C###"]
