way they do in common law systems; the court appoints the expert.\n-   **Statement iii:** This statement is incorrect. A partnership with *only* limited liability partners would be a Limited Liability Company (GmbH) or Corporation (AG), not a limited partnership. A limited partnership requires at least one partner with unlimited liability.\n\n**Eliminate Incorrect Answers**\n-   **A) none of the statements:** Incorrect, as statements ii and iii are demonstrably false.\n-   **B) iii:** Incorrect, because statement ii is also false.\n-   **C) i and ii:** Incorrect, because this option implies statement iii is correct, which is legally impossible (a limited partnership cannot consist solely of limited partners).\n\n**Conclusion**\nSince statement iii is definitely incorrect and statement ii is incorrect regarding the procedural status of party-appointed experts, the only logical combination provided is that statements ii and iii are the incorrect ones. This implies statement i is accepted as correct in this context.\n\nFinal Answer: ###D###"]
