s is **correct**. The legitimacy and cohesion of the group relied on the oath sworn by its members.\n*   **Statement iii:** \"By ways of coniuratio municipal laws could be issued and enacted.\" This is **correct**. The sworn community had the power to create its own statutes (town charters, rural codes) to secure peace and order.\n*   **Statement iv:** \"Coniuratio referred to the idea of legislation by a ruler.\" This is **incorrect**. *Coniuratio* is a horizontal association of fellows, contrasting with the vertical imposition of law by a monarch or feudal lord.\n*   **Statement v:** \"Coniuratio was a kind of customary law.\" This is **incorrect**. While customary law existed, *coniuratio* involved the deliberate, sworn enactment of rules (statutory law), making it distinct from the unwritten evolution of custom.\n\n**Eliminate Incorrect Answers**\n*   **A) ii, iii, and iv:** Incorrect because iv is false (it is not legislation by a ruler).\n*   **B) iii, iv, and v:** Incorrect because iv and v are false.\n*   **C) i, iii, and v:** Incorrect because v is false (it is not customary law).\n*   **D) i, ii, and iii:** Correct. All three statements accurately describe the nature and function of *coniuratio* in Swiss history.\n\n**Conclusion**\nStatements i, ii, and iii are correct. *Coniuratio* was the foundational legal device of the Swiss Confederation, based on the binding oath, and used to enact municipal laws.\n\nFinal Answer: ###D###"]
- Occurs in 1 rows (610): ["Here is the step-by-step reasoning to determine the correct answer:\n\n### 1. Clarify the Facts\n*   **Parties:** Dr. Genius (service provider) and Katrina (client).\n*   **Activity:** Dr. Genius estimates the value of real estate in the canton of Lucerne for Katrina.\n*   **Legal Context:** Swiss Code of Obligations (CO).\n*   **Statements to Analyze:**\n    *   i. Whether the list of contracts in the CO is exhaustive.\n    *   ii. Whether remuneration is a mandatory requirement for a simple agency contract.\n    *   iii. Whether revocation at an inopportune time triggers a liability for damages.\n\n### 2. Issue Identification\nThe core legal issues involve:\n*   **Contract Typology:** Does Swiss law recognize contracts outside the specific types listed in the CO (innominate contracts)?\n*   **Nature of Simple Agency (*Einfacher Auftrag*):** Is payment (*Entgeltlichkeit*) a constitutive element of the simple agency contract?\n*   **Termination of Agency:** What are the legal consequences under Swiss law if a client terminates a service contract (specifically a mandate) at a time that causes disadvantage to the provider?\n\n### 3. Rule Explanation\n*   **Freedom of Contract (Art. 19 CO):** Swiss law adheres to the principle of freedom of contract. Parties are free to structure their agreements as they see fit, provided they do not violate the law. This means the types of contracts listed in the Second Division of the CO (Nominate Contracts) are **not exhaustive**. Parties can create \"innominate contracts\" (e.g., leasing, franchising) that mix elements of different contracts or create new obligations entirely.\n*   **Simple Agency and Remuneration (Art. 394 CO):** The simple agency contract is defined in Art. 394 CO. Paragraph 3 specifically states: *\"A remuneration is payable if agreed or customary.\"* This implies that remuneration is **not** a mandatory element (*essentialia negotii*); a mandate can be gratuitous (free of charge).\n*   **Termination at Inopportune Time (Art. 404 CO):** A simple agency contract can be revoked or terminated by either party at any time (Art. 404 para. 1 CO). However, Art. 404 para. 2 CO states: *\"However, if the agency is revoked or notice given at an inopportune time, the revoking or giving party must compensate the other for any resultant damage.\"*\n\n### 4. Application and Reasoning\n*   **Statement i:** \"Every contract falls under one of the types in the second division of the Swiss Code of Obligations.\"\n    *   **Analysis:** This is incorrect. Due to the freedom of contract (Art. 19 CO), \"innominate contracts\" exist which do not fall strictly under the types listed in the CO.\n*   **Statement ii:** \"Paying a remuneration is in any case compulsory in order for a contract to be characterised as a simple agency contract.\"\n    *   **Analysis:** This is incorrect. Under Art. 394 para. 3 CO, a mandate is only paid if agreed or customary. A gratuitous mandate is legally valid.\n*   **Statement iii:** \"If Katrina revokes the contract at an inopportune point in time, she must compensate Dr. Genius for any resulting damage.\"\n    *   **Analysis:** The service provided by Dr. Genius (expert estimation) is typically classified as a simple agency contract (*Auftrag*) or governed by mandate law principles regarding termination. While a client has the mandatory right to terminate at any time (Art. 404 para. 1 CO), doing so \"at an inopportune time\" (*zur Unzeit*) triggers an obligation to compensate for the negative interest (damage caused by the timing of the termination), per Art. 404 para. 2 CO. Therefore, this statement is correct.\n\n### 5. Eliminate Incorrect Answers\n*   **A) ii and iii:** Incorrect because statement ii is false.\n*   **B) i:** Incorrect because statement i is false.\n*   **D) ii:** Incorrect because statement ii is false.\n*   **E) I don't know:** Not applicable.\n\n### 6. Conclusion\nOnly statement iii is legally correct based on Art. 404 para. 2 of the Swiss Code of Obligations. Consequently, Choice C is the correct answer.\n\nFinal Answer: ###C###"]
